From 9f99f9b66ec64ff305524b68bfc5f06926c6e42e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Yvette Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Sat, 13 Jun 2026 23:10:07 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 149/174] mm/pgcl: count large-folio mapcount per kernel page
 (rmap-event contract)

Under page clustering (CONFIG_PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0) a large anon folio's mapcount
is counted per KERNEL page (PAGE_SIZE) while refcount and RSS stay per MMUPAGE
hardware PTE.  Every reverse-map site must therefore emit exactly one mapcount
event per kernel page per VMA transition.  The tree fired one event per PVMW
yield / pgcl_pte_batch run, which over- or under-counts whenever a kernel
page's PAGE_MMUCOUNT sub-PTEs are not presented 1:1:

  - gaps left by partial COW / MADV_DONTNEED;
  - MMUPAGE- (not kernel-page-) aligned mappings, where mremap() /
    relocate_vma_down() keep the old vm_pgoff so the PTE-encoded sub-index
    differs from the virtual one (psub != vsub);
  - a kernel page straddling the pte-table / PMD boundary.

Symptoms (aarch64 PGCL=4, CONFIG_DEBUG_VM, cow selftest under GUP-pin migration
churn): bad_page "nonzero large_mapcount" at free and a negative _mapcount
caught at zap, on ~40% of boots.  This is the in-QEMU reproduction of the
laptop "corrupt-free page" class.

Drive every rmap site by a single kernel-page edge, detected from the page
table by physical sub-index, matching pte_pfn, and bounded to the pte table
(new helper pgcl_rmap_fire_kpage_event() in mm/internal.h):

  - zap_present_ptes(), try_to_unmap_one(), try_to_migrate_one(): fire the
    remove on the LAST present sub-PTE of the kernel page;
  - copy_present_ptes() (fork) and remove_migration_pte(): fire the add/dup
    on the FIRST present sub-PTE.

A single-sub-PTE fragment (nr == 1) of a large folio takes the edge path too,
not the generic per-PTE path.  Fork keeps the fused
folio_try_dup_anon_rmap_ptes() pin / PageAnonExclusive decision and only
suppresses the duplicate count; the pinned-and-still-exclusive case falls
through to a per-PTE copy.  The map-side Contract-B inflation is dropped
(folio_add_new_anon_rmap() already counts per kernel page).

order-0 folios keep per-PTE counting.  Every PGCL block is #if PAGE_MMUSHIFT
and collapses to mainline at shift 0 (the Newton limit), confirmed by a clean
PGCL=0 boot.

Verified on aarch64 PGCL=4, un-silenced (DEBUG_VM + DEBUG_VM_PGFLAGS +
PAGE_OWNER): 0 bad_page markers across 80+ boots (SMP=1 and SMP=4), cow + full
LTP pass, clean shutdown; a _large_mapcount/mm-id ledger never exceeds the
per-folio ceiling.  x86_64 PGCL=4 (order-0) and PGCL=0 remain clean.

For upstream the series may fold this per area; the rmap-event mechanics and
the eight invariants are written up in PGCL-RMAP-PRIMITIVES.md.

